    <node id="1. Coverage: The school categorization system has expanded from initially only covering secondary schools to now encompassing the entire range of schools.&#10;2. Judgment elements: The elements used in making categorization judgments have been adjusted over time, with changes made based on feedback and evolving requirements. This includes a shift towards looking at ways of identifying support for schools, using a risk-based approach to evaluate where resources should be spent.&#10;3. Frequency of Estyn inspections: The frequency of Estyn inspections has changed, with the initial seven-year inspection interval now evolving into a system where Estyn will be more regularly present in schools. This is part of an effort to ensure that Estyn is not just making judgments but also being part of the solution for school improvement.&#10;4. Further adjustments: While continuous improvements have been made based on feedback, there is no explicit mention of specific ongoing plans for further adjustments to the school categorization system. The speakers mainly focus on how the system has evolved and its current state rather than future changes. They do mention that both the categorization system and Estyn inspections are evolving, but no specifics are provided." />
