    <node id=" our reform journey that that's done in co-construction, because we want this resource to be usable in schools. So, it's all very well having a conceptual idea and people outside the classroom working on it, but if it's of no practical use to a school leadership team, then we won't see the impact. So, it's—. We're in phase 2 at the moment, where we're doing—. So, the initial resource has been developed by the OECD, middle tier and practitioners. We're in the testing phase at the moment and having it evaluated itself, with a view to introducing that resource across the system at the start of the new academic year, in September 2020. I truly believe that, if we're to make progress in Welsh education, we have to develop the skills within our system to have robust self-evaluation. This resource gives us continuity of approach right the way across Wales. So, it's not left to an individual school to come up with a system; it's right the way across the system. My hope would be that those principles could then be applied to local education authorities, to regional school improvement services and Welsh Government as part of a whole-system approach to self-evaluation. I don't know if" />
    <node id=" to Dylan for his hard work and his skill in chairing that group, and I think it's been welcomed by all, so that we can get that clarity and consistency about the roles and responsibilities of the individual partners and players in the middle tier.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: And when will the work be completed, and what will the outcomes be?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, the group is currently engaging with Steve and other officials on agreeing a plan, but also, crucially, that plan is there to support the successful implementation of the curriculum, so that we're very clear about the roles and responsibilities in the middle tier in this crucial phase following the publication. We have to move now from the publication into a relentless focus on implementation. The history of devolution is full of fantastic documents, and, shall I say, patchy implementation. The work that has gone into that curriculum is too important for implementation to be left to chance. It's too important. It's too good to be left to chance. So, everything now is a relentless focus on successful implementation.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: Yes, but I'm thinking that the strategic delivery is reviewing the role of the" />
    <node id="Based on the transcript, Kirsty Williams AM mentions that the 2019 data for the PDG LAC group's performance will be published next month. She acknowledges that previous data has shown underperformance in this group and has implemented measures to address this issue, including:&#10;&#10;1. Reformed approach to PDG LAC and the employment of PDG LAC coordinators across regions&#10;2. Identification of new resources for testing new approaches, such as virtual school approaches&#10;3. A focus on sustainable improvement over time by shifting from short-term fixes to long-term plans&#10;4. Development of better data analysis tools to identify potential issues in schools earlier&#10;5. Piloting the new multi-agency approach in two high schools within each local authority that have been identified as causes for concern&#10;&#10;These measures aim to address fundamental issues, evaluate the school's capacity for self-improvement, and provide additional support to the senior management team and governing body, with a focus on reducing the attainment gap between disadvantaged learners and their peers." />
    <node id=", which is one of the groups where attainment isn't where we would like it to be, there was some improvement in 2016 at key stage 4, but it has been disappointing. Do we know what's been happening in 2019?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: The 2019 data will be published next month, and there has been significant activity. You are right: in recent years, the data have been poor and not where we would want it to be. That's why we have had a reformed approach to PDG LAC; the employment of PDG LAC co-ordinators across the regions. We've identified new resource in the new financial year to test new approaches, so, for instance, virtual school approaches, where we know, in other systems, that has worked. But, we expect the next set of data around the performance of this particular group of learners in March.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Okay, and you hope to see progress.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I don't want to speculate, but I hope so.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;" />
    <node id="1. Introduction of a new multi-agency approach: The Welsh government, in collaboration with Estyn, has introduced a new multi-agency approach to identify and support schools (specifically mentioned as high schools in the provided context) requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Difference from traditional methods: In traditional methods, Estyn would make a judgment on the school and then return for another inspection after a certain period (e.g., six months). However, under this new approach, Estyn is part of the solution rather than just making judgments. The multi-agency panel, which includes Estyn, works collaboratively with the school to support its improvement continuously, creating a more integrated and supportive environment for change." />
    <node id="The group is currently engaging with officials to agree on a plan to support the successful implementation of the curriculum. This plan is crucial to ensure clarity about the roles and responsibilities in the middle tier during the implementation phase following the publication of the curriculum. The group's focus on implementation stems from the recognition that previous devolution efforts have resulted in fantastic documents but patchy implementation. The curriculum's significance and quality make it too important to be left to chance, requiring a relentless focus on successful implementation.&#10;&#10;In addition, the group will not disband after completing this task, as they have an ongoing role in overseeing the middle tier. This group operates at arm's length from the government, and while they do not report formally, they provide feedback to the Minister. The strategic delivery group is also considering a national service model with local accountability for monitoring and consistency purposes.&#10;&#10;As for the ERW (Education Through Regional Working) regional school improvement service, there are concerns about Neath Port Talbot's potential withdrawal from the consortium. While the Welsh Government does not intend to intervene directly, they seek clarification on Neath Port Talbot's plans to fulfill their functions in absence of ERW, especially considering the critical time for introducing the new curriculum. The government aims to ensure that schools and students are not disadvantaged without the support from ERW." />
