    <node id=", but we need to do more, particularly within the middle tier. This is not controlled by Government, it is arm's length from Government, and it's not their job to get it ready for the new curriculum—that's a key part of it. This group will have an ongoing role; it's not a task and finish group. It does feed back in to the Minister but there's no formal mechanism by which they have to report.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: Okay, that's very clear.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. I've got supplementaries from Suzy, then Siân.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Briefly, please.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: I think this is a really interesting evidence session. What I'm about to say, I say it even though I'm a big localist: it all seems to be heading in one direction of a national service. Is the strategic group even thinking in these terms, obviously building in local accountability? But it'll just make it so much easier in terms of accountability and consistency to monitor" />
    <node id="1. PISA's utility for school improvement: Kirsty Williams AM considers PISA as one of several useful tools for measuring school performance and systemic health. Its consistency makes it an important part of evaluating the education system, even though she acknowledges that it may not be enjoyable to monitor.&#10;&#10;2. Effective measurement of student well-being: Student well-being can be measured through a whole-school approach by assessing the overall culture and climate of the school. This method captures how the school addresses well-being rather than holding schools accountable for specific circumstances beyond their control, such as students' living conditions or family situations.&#10;&#10;3. Addressing student well-being in schools: To effectively address student well-being within a whole-school approach, proper interpretation and use of data can challenge local education authorities (LEAs) to critically think about their education system's performance. This self-reflection encourages more informed decision-making, targeted resource allocation, and the identification of specific areas for improvement.&#10;&#10;4. Avoiding complacency: Presenting data that compares local authorities should discourage complacency among those above the average or better than their neighbors. Emphasizing appropriate data use helps LEAs strive for continuous improvement in educational standards instead of settling for a false sense of security.&#10;&#10;5. Highlighting individual school impact: Proper data interpretation allows LEAs to recognize the positive impact that individual schools have on their students, even if the overall authority performance may not be as strong. This focus on individual school success can inform best practices and inspire growth across the entire education system within the local authority.&#10;&#10;In summary, PISA is a useful tool for measuring and improving school performance when used appropriately among other resources. Student well-being can be effectively measured through a whole-school approach, emphasizing self-reflection and avoiding accountability for circumstances outside of schools' control. Encouraging LEAs to continuously improve and identify specific areas in need of support will help create an education system that fosters both high academic achievement and student well-being." />
    <node id=". Exams are important—of course they are, qualifications are important—but the way in which those schools achieve those results are also important.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Would you anticipate that including well-being, then?&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: In a whole-school approach.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: I absolutely—and we need to find a way of how we can truly measure that. Sometimes, children's well-being is influenced by lots of things outside the control of a school. So, I don't want schools to be held accountable for things that they have no control over, because of the circumstances in which a child may be living. But, absolutely: well-being and how the culture of the school addresses well-being is really important to me.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. Suzy. Move on to PISA, please.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: How useful is PISA for you in helping school improvement? I know that it's not always the thing that you enjoy watching" />
    <node id="50% of school funding has been directed towards professional learning for teaching staff. This investment has been driven by evidence on international best practices and what works in driving up educational standards. Although it can be challenging to directly link specific budget allocations to particular outcomes due to the complexity of the education system, the speaker believes this investment has made a difference already and will continue to do so." />
    <node id="1. Multi-agency approach implementation: The Welsh government has introduced a new multi-agency approach to identify and support secondary schools requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Encouraging proactive local authority intervention: Local authorities are being encouraged to take a more active role in intervening and using their powers effectively. This includes developing better data analysis tools, like monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier.&#10;&#10;3. Early warning systems development: The government is looking into different sets of data that can serve as early warning systems, including carefully monitoring staff sickness levels, to further identify schools causing concern at an early stage.&#10;&#10;4. Targeted pilot program: A new pilot has been launched where local authorities identify two high schools they are particularly worried about, and a multi-agency approach is used to work with these schools and provide extra support, aiming to address the persistent challenge of moving individual secondary schools forward at a faster pace.&#10;&#10;5. Collaboration for self-evaluation resource development: The government has collaborated with organizations like the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners to develop practical and usable self-evaluation resources for schools. This effort aims to improve schools' ability to handle and educate students who repeatedly struggle with GCSEs by promoting self-evaluation in the Welsh education system as it has been underdeveloped according to various chief inspectors' reports.&#10;&#10;By implementing these measures, the Welsh government is working to address the concern that 11% of secondary schools inspected in the past two academic years were judged as unsatisfactory and in urgent need of improvement." />
