    <node id=" thank the committee for their invitation this morning, and their interest in this particular area? As you will be aware, on coming into office, the director and I agreed to ask the OECD to do a rapid review of the state of Welsh education at the beginning of this Assembly term. They did that, and the feedback from that work informed the publication and content of the national mission. I was very clear in the national mission that I would invite the OECD back to review our progress against that mission, and that has happened in the tail end of last year, and the OECD will publish their latest report on Welsh education next month now, in March. So, the expectation is that the report will be published on 23 March, and my intention is to make a statement to the Chamber on 24 March. The nature of that review is part of our ongoing development of self-evaluation. So, we talk a lot about self-evaluation in the school system. Actually, the continuing relationship with OECD is about self-evaluation of the entirety of the system and Welsh Government. We don't want to accept our own orthodoxy and just be in a bubble where we are constantly listening to ourselves and those people who might want to agree with us or tell us what we want to" />
    <node id=" It is about how that data is used, not about hiding data or making that data not available.&#10;Speaker: Steve Davies&#10;Content: Can I, very briefly—? We didn't just send a letter out collectively. We've now carried out training jointly with WLGA and Estyn on how to use that data. So, it's not just looking where your LA is; it's also not looking at whether your school's better than average for the authority. And it is well received, and it should broaden the approach of scrutiny committees to beyond what historically was, if I'm honest, looking at the league table for their authority or looking at the league table of local authorities. It's not that they shouldn't be looking at that, but they need to dig much, much deeper underneath it.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. We're going to go on now to Suzy. I'm going to appeal for brief questions and brief answers so that we can cover the rest of the questions.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: I'll shorten these questions, okay. We know why you got rid of the old measures. We've got interim measures now. What are they telling you about the" />
    <node id="1. Breadth across a range of subjects: The new third-third-third system for schools emphasizes the importance of having breadth across various subjects rather than focusing on a narrower set of subject opportunities for children. This ensures that students are exposed to and have the chance to explore different areas of learning.&#10;&#10;2. Progress for every child: The new system aims to ensure progress for every child, rather than just looking at the performance of certain cohorts or groups. This includes focusing on the impact on disadvantaged children and ensuring that they are not left behind.&#10;&#10;3. Disadvantaged backgrounds: By analyzing capped 9 scores and other data sources, schools can better understand the performance of their free school meal (FSM) eligible students and work towards reducing the attainment gap between these learners and their peers.&#10;&#10;4. Curriculum choice: The new system encourages a more diverse curriculum choice to cater to the needs and interests of all students, rather than narrowing the curriculum to focus only on subjects that are traditionally associated with high performance in exams.&#10;&#10;5. Cohorts of children with different abilities: The new third-third-third system challenges schools to look beyond just the C/D boundaries and ensure that they are pushing more able and talented students while also supporting those for whom attending school daily is an achievement. This helps create a more balanced approach to student progress and success, regardless of their ability level." />
    <node id=" sure that there is breadth across a range of subjects, rather than just focusing on a narrower and narrower bunch of subject opportunities for children, and our new third-third-third system enables schools to really look at their performance. So if their capped 9 score is high, what's driving that? Is it because the bottom third of the cohort is doing really well, and the impact on those children is above and beyond what could be expected, but actually, you're not doing very well for your more able and talented; you're not pushing them on? Alternatively, maybe your capped 9 score is because your MAT children are doing incredibly well, but actually, you're not really making the progress for the middle tier of those children. It allows us to have a greater focus on the performance of our FSM children—where they really are within that system. So, it's a much more granular—. And crucially for me, it looks at the impact for every child, because every child has to matter in the system, and what we had before was a narrowing of curriculum choice and a narrowing on a certain cohort of children.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: So are the permanent measures likely to be pretty similar to what you've got now?" />
    <node id="'ll shorten these questions, okay. We know why you got rid of the old measures. We've got interim measures now. What are they telling you about the success you've had in trying to avoid the bad behaviour? Short answers.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: It's impossible. [Laughter.] I think it's inevitable: whatever kind of measures we put in place, people will look to maximise their success in those measures, and I don't think we'll ever come up with a system where those measures are absolutely perfect. What's really important to me is that we're really, really, really challenging schools to look at the performance of all of their children, rather than just at a very, very narrow cohort around those C/D boundaries, which we knew was detrimental, potentially, to more able and talented children and really pushing those Bs to As and those As to A*s, and children for whom actually just getting in to school on a daily basis is an achievement, and the school has done well to provide that. So, our new capped 9 makes sure that there is breadth across a range of subjects, rather than just focusing on a narrower and narrower bunch of subject opportunities for children, and our new third-" />
    <node id="1. The Welsh government determines which schools require support and challenge by utilizing a variety of systems, including the school categorization system, Estyn inspection reports, and local intelligence.&#10;2. The school categorization system has evolved over time to cover the entire range of schools, with adjustments made to the elements used in making categorization judgments based on feedback and changing requirements.&#10;3. Estyn inspections have also changed, moving from a seven-year interval between inspections to a system where Estyn will be more regularly present in schools.&#10;4. Local intelligence is another factor considered when deciding what support or challenge a school may need.&#10;5. The Welsh government continuously improves the categorization system based on feedback but does not explicitly mention specific ongoing plans for further adjustments." />
    <node id="1. The effectiveness of the regional consortia, including Education Through Regional Working (ERW), is not determined by their differences in constitution and organization, but rather by their ability to deliver improvements for children and teachers.&#10;2. Kirsty Williams, the Education Minister, stated that she is interested in the effectiveness of these organizations, not their structure. She believes that larger units are necessary for successful school improvement work and warned against going back to a system where school improvement services are organized in 22 different ways (one for each local authority).&#10;3. There have been variations in performance among regional consortia, with some performing exceptionally well and others requiring improvement. However, there is no specific concern mentioned about ERW's effectiveness compared to the other consortia.&#10;4. The focus remains on ensuring that school improvement services, whether provided by regional consortia or local authorities, are effective in delivering positive outcomes for children and teachers. This includes investing in professional learning for teaching staff, which has been shown to drive up educational standards." />
    <node id="1. Expansion of coverage: The school categorization system has evolved from initially only covering secondary schools to now encompassing the entire range of schools. This expansion allows for a more comprehensive assessment of educational institutions at all levels.&#10;2. Changes in judgment elements: Over time, the elements used in making categorization judgments have shifted away from being solely data-driven. Adjustments have been made based on feedback and evolving requirements to create a more holistic evaluation method that includes both data and the Estyn inspection regime.&#10;3. Increased frequency of Estyn inspections: The interval between Estyn inspections has changed, with the initial seven-year period now evolving into a system where Estyn is more regularly present in schools. This shift allows for continuous evaluation and support, rather than periodic judgments.&#10;4. Introduction of multi-agency approach: In addition to these changes, the Welsh government and Estyn have introduced a new multi-agency approach to identify and support schools requiring significant improvement and special measures. This collaborative method focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating self-improvement capacity, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body, further enhancing the overall system's effectiveness in promoting school improvement." />
