    <edge source=" regard to changes to performance measures—you're right that change to those does make it, in some cases, more difficult to look at trends over a period of time. But those changes are made for really good reasons. If we change a performance measure, it is done to ensure that it is in the best interests of learners. And I think the best interests of learners always trumps the ease of comparison. I understand that, for researchers and for opposition Members, even for Ministers, it would be simpler to have the same set of measures over a period of time. But if we know that those things are driving behaviours that are unhelpful to children, and not in the best interests of children, then we have to change them, even thought that then does create challenges in different areas. With regard to what do we look at, there are a number of ways that we gain data and look at data in the system: everything from the categorisation system we spoke of earlier, and trends in categorisation; we look at Estyn reports; we continue to look at examination results. But we're trying to develop a broader range of data and statistics that give us a whole picture of the education performance, rather than narrowing down on one simple indicator that tells you one thing but" target="1. Introduction of a more able and talented budget and the Seren programme: A specific budget has been introduced to support the growth and development of more able and talented children, particularly in improving their performance at higher levels (Level 5 and Level 6). The Seren program will focus on post-16 students but will also introduce its principles earlier in children's education, starting from Year 9. This initiative aims to drive overall improvements in student performance.&#10;&#10;2. Focusing on reading skills, especially for boys: Recognizing the significant gap between Welsh students and their UK counterparts, as well as a notable disparity between girls' and boys' reading scores, efforts are being made to work with southern Ireland to learn from their success and improve the reading skills of Welsh children, particularly boys.&#10;&#10;3. Maintaining support for math and science: Although there have been some successes and encouragement in math and science, the new budget and Seren program do not aim to shift focus away from these subjects. The goal is to ensure that improvements in other areas do not come at the expense of success in math and science.&#10;&#10;4. Sustainable improvement: A more strategic, longer-term approach will be taken to address underlying challenges in schools, ensuring that any improvements made are sustainable and not just short-term gains achieved through &quot;easy wins.&quot; This approach aims to tackle deeper issues within schools that may cause them to slip back after initial improvements.&#10;&#10;5. Supporting minority ethnic learners: A ring-fenced grant of £10 million will be maintained for local authorities to support the education of minority ethnic children, with a commitment to having a more sophisticated conversation about what is really going on in attainment across minority ethnic groups. This will help best target resources and understand differences within this diverse group.">
