    <edge source=" regard to changes to performance measures—you're right that change to those does make it, in some cases, more difficult to look at trends over a period of time. But those changes are made for really good reasons. If we change a performance measure, it is done to ensure that it is in the best interests of learners. And I think the best interests of learners always trumps the ease of comparison. I understand that, for researchers and for opposition Members, even for Ministers, it would be simpler to have the same set of measures over a period of time. But if we know that those things are driving behaviours that are unhelpful to children, and not in the best interests of children, then we have to change them, even thought that then does create challenges in different areas. With regard to what do we look at, there are a number of ways that we gain data and look at data in the system: everything from the categorisation system we spoke of earlier, and trends in categorisation; we look at Estyn reports; we continue to look at examination results. But we're trying to develop a broader range of data and statistics that give us a whole picture of the education performance, rather than narrowing down on one simple indicator that tells you one thing but" target="1. The previous performance measure around English literature GCSE resulted in significant numbers of children, particularly those entitled to free school meals, not sitting for the exam. This led to a narrow focus on certain parts of the cohort and curriculum.&#10;2. The performance measure was changed last year, leading to a significant increase in the number of children sitting for the English literature GCSE. This change is beneficial as studying literature is essential for the development of literacy and oracy standards, introducing children to the joy of reading and the written word. It also helps reduce the attainment gap between pupils who are eligible for free school meals and those who are not.&#10;3. The change in performance measures has resulted in the need to consider more indicators and gather evidence from different sources, which can be challenging. However, the Welsh government believes that the best interests of learners should always be the primary concern, even if it makes assessments more complex or difficult to compare over time.&#10;4. The government is developing a broader range of data and statistics to gain a whole picture of the education performance, rather than focusing on a single simple indicator. This approach will provide a more comprehensive and accurate assessment of the education system in Wales.">
