    <edge source="Content: Thanks for that. I think, for any impartial reader of the way that the trends have been going on this, there is some good news within that, in that, certainly, those schools that might have been identified as have been okay but coasting along, seem to be moving up the categories, although we still do have that—. Well, it's what the system is there to do, it's to identify those schools that do need that additional support. And I like your analogy of a triage system—'You're fit; keep on doing what you're doing and do it well; you need more support, we'll put the support in.' But, can I turn to those schools that are causing significant concern, and how we identify them? The Estyn chief inspector's conclusions at the end of the 2017-18 report that these schools are not being identified early enough—there's a need to do something urgently about these concerns, particularly in secondary schools. Have we addressed that? Are you content that we've addressed that concern? Was he right?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: No, the chief inspector is absolutely right—absolutely right. I've got no beef with that statement at all. In some ways, when" target="1. Introduction of a new multi-agency approach: The Welsh government has introduced a multi-agency approach to identify and support schools requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Proactive local authority intervention: The government is encouraging local authorities to take a proactive approach to intervention and use their powers effectively. This includes developing better data analysis tools, such as monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier.&#10;&#10;3. Early warning systems: To further identify schools causing concern at an early stage, the government is looking into different sets of data that can serve as early warning systems, including carefully monitoring staff sickness levels. High levels of staff sickness have been found to correlate with issues within a school.&#10;&#10;4. Targeted pilot program: A new pilot has been launched in which local authorities identify two high schools they are particularly worried about. A multi-agency approach is used to work with these schools and provide extra support, aiming to address the persistent challenge of moving individual secondary schools forward at a faster pace.&#10;&#10;5. Improved collaboration: The government has collaborated with organizations like the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners to develop practical and usable self-evaluation resources for schools, promoting self-evaluation in the Welsh education system as it has been underdeveloped according to various chief inspectors' reports.">
