    <edge source=" to actually make that difference over time.&#10;Speaker: Huw Irranca-Davies AM&#10;Content: Okay. So, does that—. I'd love to go further, but time is against us. Does that deal with the issue of the schools that have been identified in those categories of requiring significant improvement and requiring special measures? Are those the ones that will be identified now, or is that above and beyond that again?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, those are the ones that are primarily at the forefront of our minds, but this way of sharing data better, to step in earlier, is part of our attempt to address what the chief inspector says about stepping in early—not waiting until a school gets into special measures and a formal judgment from Estyn of that, but actually using that intelligence to get support in there earlier. The three elements that that multi-agency approach look at are: what are the fundamentals that need addressing in this school? What is the capacity of the school itself to be able to address those fundamentals? And, what extra support needs to go into that senior management team and the governing body to get those fundamentals addressed? And actually, what does sustainable improvement look like? Because, again, one" target="1. Introduction of a new multi-agency approach: The Welsh government has introduced a multi-agency approach to identify and support schools requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Proactive local authority intervention: The government is encouraging local authorities to take a proactive approach to intervention and use their powers effectively. This includes developing better data analysis tools, such as monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier.&#10;&#10;3. Early warning systems: To further identify schools causing concern at an early stage, the government is looking into different sets of data that can serve as early warning systems, including carefully monitoring staff sickness levels. High levels of staff sickness have been found to correlate with issues within a school.&#10;&#10;4. Targeted pilot program: A new pilot has been launched in which local authorities identify two high schools they are particularly worried about. A multi-agency approach is used to work with these schools and provide extra support, aiming to address the persistent challenge of moving individual secondary schools forward at a faster pace.&#10;&#10;5. Improved collaboration: The government has collaborated with organizations like the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners to develop practical and usable self-evaluation resources for schools, promoting self-evaluation in the Welsh education system as it has been underdeveloped according to various chief inspectors' reports.">
