    <edge source="1. Introduction of a more able and talented budget and the Seren programme: A specific budget has been introduced to support the growth and development of more able and talented children, particularly in improving their performance at higher levels (Level 5 and Level 6). The Seren program will focus on post-16 students but will also introduce its principles earlier in children's education, starting from Year 9. This initiative aims to drive overall improvements in student performance.&#10;&#10;2. Focusing on reading skills, especially for boys: Recognizing the significant gap between Welsh students and their UK counterparts, as well as a notable disparity between girls' and boys' reading scores, efforts are being made to work with southern Ireland to learn from their success and improve the reading skills of Welsh children, particularly boys.&#10;&#10;3. Maintaining support for math and science: Although there have been some successes and encouragement in math and science, the new budget and Seren program do not aim to shift focus away from these subjects. The goal is to ensure that improvements in other areas do not come at the expense of success in math and science.&#10;&#10;4. Sustainable improvement: A more strategic, longer-term approach will be taken to address underlying challenges in schools, ensuring that any improvements made are sustainable and not just short-term gains achieved through &quot;easy wins.&quot; This approach aims to tackle deeper issues within schools that may cause them to slip back after initial improvements.&#10;&#10;5. Supporting minority ethnic learners: A ring-fenced grant of £10 million will be maintained for local authorities to support the education of minority ethnic children, with a commitment to having a more sophisticated conversation about what is really going on in attainment across minority ethnic groups. This will help best target resources and understand differences within this diverse group." target=" Su