    <edge source="50 percent of school funding has been directed towards professional learning for teaching staff. This investment has been driven by evidence on international best practices and what works in driving up educational standards. The speaker highlights that it is challenging to directly link the spending of a specific portion of the budget to particular outcomes, given the complexity of the education system. However, they believe that this investment in staff professional development has made a difference already and will continue to do so, as it aligns with what is known to work in improving educational standards." target="1. Comparisons can be misleading: Local education authorities (LEAs) should not rely solely on being above the national average or comparing themselves to neighboring authorities because such comparisons can be misleading. A local authority that is above the national average may still have room for improvement, and complacency could hinder further progress.&#10;2. Encouraging self-reflection: Proper interpretation and use of data challenge LEAs to think critically about their education system's performance. This approach encourages self-reflection and promotes a deeper understanding of the strengths and weaknesses within the local education authority, leading to more informed decision-making.&#10;3. Identifying areas for improvement: When LEAs pay close attention to their data, they are better equipped to identify specific areas where improvements are needed. This focus on granular data can help target resources and support more effectively, ultimately benefiting schools and students within the authority.&#10;4. Avoiding a false sense of security: Presenting data that compares local authorities can create a false sense of security for those above the average or better than their neighbors. By emphasizing appropriate data use, LEAs are discouraged from becoming complacent and prompted to strive for continuous improvement in educational standards.&#10;5. Highlighting individual school impact: Proper data interpretation helps LEAs recognize the positive impact that individual schools have on their students, even if the overall authority performance may not be as strong. This focus on individual school success can inform best practices and inspire growth across the entire education system within the local authority.">
