    <edge source="50 percent of school funding has been directed towards professional learning for teaching staff. This investment has been driven by evidence on international best practices and what works in driving up educational standards. The speaker highlights that it is challenging to directly link the spending of a specific portion of the budget to particular outcomes, given the complexity of the education system. However, they believe that this investment in staff professional development has made a difference already and will continue to do so, as it aligns with what is known to work in improving educational standards." target="1. Mixed performance among regional consortia: Kirsty Williams, the Education Minister, has acknowledged that there are variations in the performance of school improvement services provided by different regional consortia. Some have performed exceptionally well, while others need improvement. She did not express any specific concern regarding ERW's effectiveness compared to the other consortia.&#10;2. Neath Port Talbot's withdrawal from ERW: The Welsh Government is currently seeking clarification on how Neath Port Talbot intends to support its schools and teachers if they withdraw from ERW. There are concerns about the potential disadvantage for Neath Port Talbot's students due to a lack of regional consortium support, as well as challenges in fulfilling educational functions without ERW. No direct intervention is planned by the Welsh Government at this stage.&#10;3. Investment in professional learning: A significant portion (50%) of school funding has been directed towards professional learning for teaching staff, driven by evidence on international best practices and what works in driving up educational standards. While it can be challenging to directly link specific budget allocations to particular outcomes due to the education system's complexity, the speaker believes this investment has made a difference already and will continue to do so.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, while there are concerns about Neath Port Talbot's withdrawal from ERW and its impact on local schools and students, there is no explicit mention of ERW being less effective than the other consortia due to its different approach. The focus remains on ensuring that school improvement services, whether provided by regional consortia or local authorities, are effective in delivering positive outcomes for children and teachers.">
