    <edge source="The Welsh government is taking several measures to address schools requiring significant improvement and special measures. A new multi-agency approach has been introduced to identify and support these schools earlier, focusing on three main elements: addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;This approach also aims to ensure sustainable improvement over time by shifting from short-term fixes to a more strategic, long-term plan. The government is working on developing better data analysis tools, such as monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier. They are also piloting this new multi-agency approach in two high schools within each local authority that have been identified as causes for concern.&#10;&#10;Furthermore, the government is encouraging local authorities to take a proactive approach to intervention and use their powers effectively. A national evaluation and improvement resource has been established to promote self-evaluation in schools, which has been underdeveloped in the Welsh education system according to various chief inspectors' reports. This resource aims to be practical and usable for schools, as it has been developed in collaboration with the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners." target="1. The previous performance measure around English literature GCSE resulted in significant numbers of children, particularly those entitled to free school meals, not sitting for the exam. This led to a narrow focus on certain parts of the cohort and curriculum.&#10;2. The performance measure was changed last year, leading to a significant increase in the number of children sitting for the English literature GCSE. This change is beneficial as studying literature is essential for the development of literacy and oracy standards, introducing children to the joy of reading and the written word. It also helps reduce the attainment gap between pupils who are eligible for free school meals and those who are not.&#10;3. The change in performance measures has resulted in the need to consider more indicators and gather evidence from different sources, which can be challenging. However, the Welsh government believes that the best interests of learners should always be the primary concern, even if it makes assessments more complex or difficult to compare over time.&#10;4. The government is developing a broader range of data and statistics to gain a whole picture of the education performance, rather than focusing on a single simple indicator. This approach will provide a more comprehensive and accurate assessment of the education system in Wales.">
