    <edge source="The Welsh government is taking several measures to address schools requiring significant improvement and special measures. A new multi-agency approach has been introduced to identify and support these schools earlier, focusing on three main elements: addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;This approach also aims to ensure sustainable improvement over time by shifting from short-term fixes to a more strategic, long-term plan. The government is working on developing better data analysis tools, such as monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier. They are also piloting this new multi-agency approach in two high schools within each local authority that have been identified as causes for concern.&#10;&#10;Furthermore, the government is encouraging local authorities to take a proactive approach to intervention and use their powers effectively. A national evaluation and improvement resource has been established to promote self-evaluation in schools, which has been underdeveloped in the Welsh education system according to various chief inspectors' reports. This resource aims to be practical and usable for schools, as it has been developed in collaboration with the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners." target="1. Introduction of a new multi-agency approach: The Welsh government has introduced a multi-agency approach to identify and support schools requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Proactive local authority intervention: The government is encouraging local authorities to take a proactive approach to intervention and use their powers effectively. This includes developing better data analysis tools, such as monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier.&#10;&#10;3. Early warning systems: To further identify schools causing concern at an early stage, the government is looking into different sets of data that can serve as early warning systems, including carefully monitoring staff sickness levels. High levels of staff sickness have been found to correlate with issues within a school.&#10;&#10;4. Targeted pilot program: A new pilot has been launched in which local authorities identify two high schools they are particularly worried about. A multi-agency approach is used to work with these schools and provide extra support, aiming to address the persistent challenge of moving individual secondary schools forward at a faster pace.&#10;&#10;5. Improved collaboration: The government has collaborated with organizations like the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners to develop practical and usable self-evaluation resources for schools, promoting self-evaluation in the Welsh education system as it has been underdeveloped according to various chief inspectors' reports.">
