    <edge source="The Welsh government is taking several measures to address schools requiring significant improvement and special measures. A new multi-agency approach has been introduced to identify and support these schools earlier, focusing on three main elements: addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;This approach also aims to ensure sustainable improvement over time by shifting from short-term fixes to a more strategic, long-term plan. The government is working on developing better data analysis tools, such as monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier. They are also piloting this new multi-agency approach in two high schools within each local authority that have been identified as causes for concern.&#10;&#10;Furthermore, the government is encouraging local authorities to take a proactive approach to intervention and use their powers effectively. A national evaluation and improvement resource has been established to promote self-evaluation in schools, which has been underdeveloped in the Welsh education system according to various chief inspectors' reports. This resource aims to be practical and usable for schools, as it has been developed in collaboration with the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners." target="1. Introduction of a new multi-agency approach: The Welsh government, in collaboration with Estyn, has introduced a new multi-agency approach to identify and support schools (specifically mentioned as high schools in the provided context) requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Difference from traditional methods: In traditional methods, Estyn would make a judgment on the school and then return for another inspection after a certain period (e.g., six months). However, under this new approach, Estyn is part of the solution rather than just making judgments. The multi-agency panel, which includes Estyn, works collaboratively with the school to support its improvement continuously, creating a more integrated and supportive environment for change.">
