    <edge source="1. Recent changes in performance measures for English literature GCSE exams in Wales have had a positive impact on the number of students taking the exam, especially those entitled to free school meals.&#10;2. Previously, a performance measure around English was introduced which led to significant numbers of children, particularly those entitled to free school meals, not sitting for the English literature GCSE.&#10;3. This performance measure was changed last year, resulting in a significant increase in the number of children sitting for the English literature GCSE.&#10;4. The rationale behind these changes is that studying literature is essential for the development of literacy and oracy standards, introducing children to the joy of reading and the written word. It also helps in reducing the attainment gap between pupils who are eligible for free school meals and those who are not." target=" it does present more of a challenge, presumably, because you have to look at more indicators, and take evidence from different places. But I take it that you're confident that the trajectory is going in the right way.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Yes, I think we are making improvements. But you're right: it does make it more challenging. But those changes are being made for the right reasons, as I said, whether that be at level 2 plus. Look at English literature. I understand why perhaps a performance measure around English was introduced, but the effect of that was that significant numbers of children—and, it must be said, usually children who are entitled to free school meals—were suddenly not sitting English literature GCSE. We've changed that performance measure, and guess what? Last year, we saw a significant increase in the number of children that were sitting English literature GCSE. For standards of literacy and oracy, I think studying literature is really, really important, before we even get into the joy of introducing children to the written word and the love of reading. So, we make changes. Yes, it causes challenges, but we're making those changes because we believe that they are in the best interest of children, and">
