    <edge source="1. Introduction of a new multi-agency approach: The Welsh government has introduced a multi-agency approach to identify and support schools requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Proactive local authority intervention: The government is encouraging local authorities to take a proactive approach to intervention and use their powers effectively. This includes developing better data analysis tools, such as monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier.&#10;&#10;3. Early warning systems: To further identify schools causing concern at an early stage, the government is looking into different sets of data that can serve as early warning systems, including carefully monitoring staff sickness levels. High levels of staff sickness have been found to correlate with issues within a school.&#10;&#10;4. Targeted pilot program: A new pilot has been launched in which local authorities identify two high schools they are particularly worried about. A multi-agency approach is used to work with these schools and provide extra support, aiming to address the persistent challenge of moving individual secondary schools forward at a faster pace.&#10;&#10;5. Improved collaboration: The government has collaborated with organizations like the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners to develop practical and usable self-evaluation resources for schools, promoting self-evaluation in the Welsh education system as it has been underdeveloped according to various chief inspectors' reports." target="1. Multi-agency approach: The Welsh government has introduced a new multi-agency approach to identify and support secondary schools requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach aims to address fundamental issues within the school, evaluate its capacity for self-improvement, and provide additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Early warning systems: To better identify schools causing concern at an early stage, the government is looking into different sets of data, including carefully monitoring staff sickness levels. High levels of staff sickness have been found to correlate with issues within a school.&#10;&#10;3. Targeted pilot program: A new pilot has been launched in which local authorities identify two high schools they are particularly worried about. A multi-agency approach is used to work with these schools and provide extra support, aiming to address the persistent challenge of moving individual secondary schools forward at a faster pace. This pilot program is being evaluated by Cardiff Metropolitan University and Swansea University to assess its effectiveness.&#10;&#10;4. Collaboration: The government has collaborated with organizations like the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners to develop practical and usable self-evaluation resources for schools, promoting self-evaluation in the Welsh education system as it has been underdeveloped according to various chief inspectors' reports. This is expected to improve schools' ability to handle and educate students who repeatedly struggle with GCSEs.">
