    <edge source="Based on the transcript, Kirsty Williams AM mentions that the 2019 data for the PDG LAC group's performance will be published next month. She acknowledges that previous data has shown underperformance in this group and has implemented measures to address this issue, including:&#10;&#10;1. Reformed approach to PDG LAC and the employment of PDG LAC coordinators across regions&#10;2. Identification of new resources for testing new approaches, such as virtual school approaches&#10;3. A focus on sustainable improvement over time by shifting from short-term fixes to long-term plans&#10;4. Development of better data analysis tools to identify potential issues in schools earlier&#10;5. Piloting the new multi-agency approach in two high schools within each local authority that have been identified as causes for concern&#10;&#10;These measures aim to address fundamental issues, evaluate the school's capacity for self-improvement, and provide additional support to the senior management team and governing body, with a focus on reducing the attainment gap between disadvantaged learners and their peers." target="1. PISA's utility for school improvement: Kirsty Williams AM considers PISA as one of several useful tools for measuring school performance and systemic health. Its consistency makes it an important part of evaluating the education system, even though she acknowledges that it may not be enjoyable to monitor.&#10;&#10;2. Effective measurement of student well-being: Student well-being can be measured through a whole-school approach by assessing the overall culture and climate of the school. This method captures how the school addresses well-being rather than holding schools accountable for specific circumstances beyond their control, such as students' living conditions or family situations.&#10;&#10;3. Addressing student well-being in schools: To effectively address student well-being within a whole-school approach, proper interpretation and use of data can challenge local education authorities (LEAs) to critically think about their education system's performance. This self-reflection encourages more informed decision-making, targeted resource allocation, and the identification of specific areas for improvement.&#10;&#10;4. Avoiding complacency: Presenting data that compares local authorities should discourage complacency among those above the average or better than their neighbors. Emphasizing appropriate data use helps LEAs strive for continuous improvement in educational standards instead of settling for a false sense of security.&#10;&#10;5. Highlighting individual school impact: Proper data interpretation allows LEAs to recognize the positive impact that individual schools have on their students, even if the overall authority performance may not be as strong. This focus on individual school success can inform best practices and inspire growth across the entire education system within the local authority.&#10;&#10;In summary, PISA is a useful tool for measuring and improving school performance when used appropriately among other resources. Student well-being can be effectively measured through a whole-school approach, emphasizing self-reflection and avoiding accountability for circumstances outside of schools' control. Encouraging LEAs to continuously improve and identify specific areas in need of support will help create an education system that fosters both high academic achievement and student well-being.">
