    <edge source="Based on the transcript, Kirsty Williams AM mentions that the 2019 data for the PDG LAC group's performance will be published next month. She acknowledges that previous data has shown underperformance in this group and has implemented measures to address this issue, including:&#10;&#10;1. Reformed approach to PDG LAC and the employment of PDG LAC coordinators across regions&#10;2. Identification of new resources for testing new approaches, such as virtual school approaches&#10;3. A focus on sustainable improvement over time by shifting from short-term fixes to long-term plans&#10;4. Development of better data analysis tools to identify potential issues in schools earlier&#10;5. Piloting the new multi-agency approach in two high schools within each local authority that have been identified as causes for concern&#10;&#10;These measures aim to address fundamental issues, evaluate the school's capacity for self-improvement, and provide additional support to the senior management team and governing body, with a focus on reducing the attainment gap between disadvantaged learners and their peers." target="1. Breadth across a range of subjects: The new third-third-third system for schools emphasizes the importance of having breadth across various subjects rather than focusing on a narrower set of subject opportunities for children. This ensures that students are exposed to and have the chance to explore different areas of learning.&#10;&#10;2. Progress for every child: The new system aims to ensure progress for every child, rather than just looking at the performance of certain cohorts or groups. This includes focusing on the impact on disadvantaged children and ensuring that they are not left behind.&#10;&#10;3. Disadvantaged backgrounds: By analyzing capped 9 scores and other data sources, schools can better understand the performance of their free school meal (FSM) eligible students and work towards reducing the attainment gap between these learners and their peers.&#10;&#10;4. Curriculum choice: The new system encourages a more diverse curriculum choice to cater to the needs and interests of all students, rather than narrowing the curriculum to focus only on subjects that are traditionally associated with high performance in exams.&#10;&#10;5. Cohorts of children with different abilities: The new third-third-third system challenges schools to look beyond just the C/D boundaries and ensure that they are pushing more able and talented students while also supporting those for whom attending school daily is an achievement. This helps create a more balanced approach to student progress and success, regardless of their ability level.">
