    <edge source="1. Introduction of a new multi-agency approach: The Welsh government, in collaboration with Estyn, has introduced a new multi-agency approach to identify and support schools (specifically mentioned as high schools in the provided context) requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Difference from traditional methods: In traditional methods, Estyn would make a judgment on the school and then return for another inspection after a certain period (e.g., six months). However, under this new approach, Estyn is part of the solution rather than just making judgments. The multi-agency panel, which includes Estyn, works collaboratively with the school to support its improvement continuously, creating a more integrated and supportive environment for change." target="1. The Welsh government determines which schools require support and challenge by utilizing a variety of systems, including the school categorization system, Estyn inspection reports, and local intelligence.&#10;2. The school categorization system has evolved over time to cover the entire range of schools, with adjustments made to the elements used in making categorization judgments based on feedback and changing requirements.&#10;3. Estyn inspections have also changed, moving from a seven-year interval between inspections to a system where Estyn will be more regularly present in schools.&#10;4. Local intelligence is another factor considered when deciding what support or challenge a school may need.&#10;5. The Welsh government continuously improves the categorization system based on feedback but does not explicitly mention specific ongoing plans for further adjustments.">
