    <edge source="50% of school funding has been directed towards professional learning for teaching staff. This investment has been driven by evidence on international best practices and what works in driving up educational standards. Although it can be challenging to directly link specific budget allocations to particular outcomes due to the complexity of the education system, the speaker believes this investment has made a difference already and will continue to do so." target="1. Multi-agency approach implementation: The Welsh government has introduced a new multi-agency approach to identify and support secondary schools requiring significant improvement and special measures earlier. This approach focuses on addressing fundamental issues within the school, evaluating the school's capacity for self-improvement, and providing additional support to the senior management team and governing body.&#10;&#10;2. Encouraging proactive local authority intervention: Local authorities are being encouraged to take a more active role in intervening and using their powers effectively. This includes developing better data analysis tools, like monitoring staff sickness rates, to identify potential issues in schools earlier.&#10;&#10;3. Early warning systems development: The government is looking into different sets of data that can serve as early warning systems, including carefully monitoring staff sickness levels, to further identify schools causing concern at an early stage.&#10;&#10;4. Targeted pilot program: A new pilot has been launched where local authorities identify two high schools they are particularly worried about, and a multi-agency approach is used to work with these schools and provide extra support, aiming to address the persistent challenge of moving individual secondary schools forward at a faster pace.&#10;&#10;5. Collaboration for self-evaluation resource development: The government has collaborated with organizations like the OECD, middle tier, and practitioners to develop practical and usable self-evaluation resources for schools. This effort aims to improve schools' ability to handle and educate students who repeatedly struggle with GCSEs by promoting self-evaluation in the Welsh education system as it has been underdeveloped according to various chief inspectors' reports.&#10;&#10;By implementing these measures, the Welsh government is working to address the concern that 11% of secondary schools inspected in the past two academic years were judged as unsatisfactory and in urgent need of improvement.">
