    <edge source="1. Breadth across a range of subjects: The new third-third-third system for schools emphasizes the importance of having breadth across various subjects rather than focusing on a narrower set of subject opportunities for children. This ensures that students are exposed to and have the chance to explore different areas of learning.&#10;&#10;2. Progress for every child: The new system aims to ensure progress for every child, rather than just looking at the performance of certain cohorts or groups. This includes focusing on the impact on disadvantaged children and ensuring that they are not left behind.&#10;&#10;3. Disadvantaged backgrounds: By analyzing capped 9 scores and other data sources, schools can better understand the performance of their free school meal (FSM) eligible students and work towards reducing the attainment gap between these learners and their peers.&#10;&#10;4. Curriculum choice: The new system encourages a more diverse curriculum choice to cater to the needs and interests of all students, rather than narrowing the curriculum to focus only on subjects that are traditionally associated with high performance in exams.&#10;&#10;5. Cohorts of children with different abilities: The new third-third-third system challenges schools to look beyond just the C/D boundaries and ensure that they are pushing more able and talented students while also supporting those for whom attending school daily is an achievement. This helps create a more balanced approach to student progress and success, regardless of their ability level." target=" sure that there is breadth across a range of subjects, rather than just focusing on a narrower and narrower bunch of subject opportunities for children, and our new third-third-third system enables schools to really look at their performance. So if their capped 9 score is high, what's driving that? Is it because the bottom third of the cohort is doing really well, and the impact on those children is above and beyond what could be expected, but actually, you're not doing very well for your more able and talented; you're not pushing them on? Alternatively, maybe your capped 9 score is because your MAT children are doing incredibly well, but actually, you're not really making the progress for the middle tier of those children. It allows us to have a greater focus on the performance of our FSM children—where they really are within that system. So, it's a much more granular—. And crucially for me, it looks at the impact for every child, because every child has to matter in the system, and what we had before was a narrowing of curriculum choice and a narrowing on a certain cohort of children.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: So are the permanent measures likely to be pretty similar to what you've got now?">
